com:
https://youtu.be/BoJ6PnlvpZs
Its so wonderfully heavy, the marshall stacks they used live absolutely changed the game. Jack and Ginger are in top form and really live up to their reputation as the greatest rhythm section in rock music, groove after groove. It also contains some of the tastiest licks Eric has ever laid down in his entire career. They work as such a cohesive unit but their individual talents still fully shine, they really were the Cream of the Crop of 60s musicians. You can totally hear the blueprint for later heavy rock legends like Led Zeppelin and ESPECIALLY Black Sabbath. Its psychedelic bluesy heavy rock in its most archetypal form. I can listen to this recording over and over again and never get bored, I'd happily sacrifice my pinky fingers to go back to '68 and watch them slay this live.
sub: The Wheels of Fire live version of Spoonful is the absolute pinnacle of blues-rock

top 5 favourite radiohead songs (mostly no order)
>the tourist
This is my favourite radiohead song. Just an amazing track. Everything comes together perfectly from the singing, to the guitars to the drumming. It’s gorgeous
>daydreaming
Extremely delicate but with a big presence. Ethereal piano motif, soft ambient vocal sampling. Amazing track
>Everything In Its Right Place
Maybe the best chord progression I’ve ever heard even though it’s not that complex. Classic vocals and an unforgettable opening to the track. A timeless piece of pop music
>How to disappear completely
stereotypically sad Radiohead song, but the lyrics are relatable for a lot of people and the instrumentation and melody are fantastic. The walking bass motif compliments the soft guitar chords so perfectly and the gentle backdrop of string arrangements add a lot of weight to the track, not to mention the intense emotion of Thom’s vocals
>True Love Waits

Wait what does the “b” in bIII mean

Does that represent a minor or “flattened” third or something', 'time': 1670824564, 'resto': 114008661}, {'no': 114009407, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)01:17:13', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>114009226
the 'b' means that the root of the chord is a half-step down from root of that chord relative to key it's in. If the capitalization of the roman numerals is in Upper case, it's a major chord. If lower case, it's a minor chord.

So for example if there was a chord labeled iii for a song in the key of C major, it would chord built on the third note of a C major scale which is an E minor chord (E G B). If i add a 'b' and make it biii, the root of the chord becomes an Eb. Since an e flat chord is outside the key of C, we look at the capitalization to determine if it's major or minor. So if it's labeled bIII, it's an Eb major chord. If it's labeled biii it's an Eb minor chord.

Hope that helped', 'time': 1670825833, 'resto': 114008661}, {'no': 114009542, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)01:33:50', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>114009407
